{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8daabc6-d57c-40a1-85c7-bbd0a24c785c","content":"In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work as before. However, the recommended modern approach is to use **`Window` lifecycle events**, which give you finer-grained control:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `Backgrounding` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\n**Option 1 — Subscribe in `CreateWindow`:**\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\nAdditional useful events: `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding` (for saving state on iOS).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75797ca4-d1b6-4c19-a6d4-3a0b6746f246","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent approach is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. The `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`. Instead, you work with `Window` events:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `CreateWindow`\n\n\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Backgrounding` or `Window.Deactivated`\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`\n\nActually, I should clarify that .NET MAUI still supports `Application` lifecycle methods, but the preferred approach is using the `Window` events instead.\n\nThe `Window` class provides more granular control with events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding`. I can override `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class to hook into these events.","outputTokens":981,"requestId":"1424:28B932:6B1DF32:7377204:6A03CD3C"},"id":"6849e8b6-d1e0-4e31-a213-b3443938b69d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:01:02.249Z","parentId":"2d535a2a-f6f4-4724-8077-b34935de0603"}
